        <section class="info-section">
            <div class="info-container">
                <h2>Optimal Nutrition for Cows</h2>
                <p>Nutrition is the cornerstone of cow health. A balanced diet should include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Forage:</strong> High-quality hay, silage, and pasture grasses.</li>
                    <li><strong>Concentrates:</strong> Grains like corn and barley for energy supplementation.</li>
                    <li><strong>Supplements:</strong> Minerals, vitamins, and protein-rich feed.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Ensure constant access to clean water, and adjust feeding based on the cow's life stage and production
                    level.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Environmental Needs -->
        <section class="info-section">
            <div class="info-container">
                <h2>Ideal Environmental Conditions</h2>
                <p>Cows thrive in environments that provide comfort and safety. Consider the following:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Climate Control:</strong> Shelter from extreme weather conditions is essential.</li>
                    <li><strong>Bedding:</strong> Use clean, dry bedding like straw or sand to keep cows comfortable.
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Space:</strong> Ensure adequate space for movement to reduce stress and injuries.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Regularly clean and maintain facilities to promote a healthy living environment.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Common Diseases and Prevention -->
        <section class="info-section">
            <div class="info-container">
                <h2>Health Challenges and Disease Prevention</h2>
                <p>Preventing and managing diseases is critical for maintaining a healthy herd:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Bovine Respiratory Disease (BRD):</strong> Monitor for symptoms like coughing and nasal
                        discharge; vaccinate as needed.</li>
                    <li><strong>Mastitis:</strong> Regular milking hygiene practices can prevent this common udder
                        infection.</li>
                    <li><strong>Foot Rot:</strong> Ensure dry, clean environments and treat early with antibiotics.
                    </li>
                </ul>
                <p>Work closely with a veterinarian to develop a health management plan tailored to your herd.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Health Maintenance and Best Practices -->
        <section class="info-section">
            <div class="info-container">
                <h2>Maintaining Optimal Health</h2>
                <p>Keeping cows healthy requires consistent management practices:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Regular Check-ups:</strong> Schedule routine veterinary visits for health assessments.
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Parasite Control:</strong> Implement deworming programs and manage external parasites
                        like ticks and flies.</li>
                    <li><strong>Nutrition Management:</strong> Regularly evaluate and adjust diets to meet the changing
                        needs of your cows.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Maintain detailed health records for each cow to track treatments, vaccinations, and health history.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Breeding and Reproductive Health -->
        <section class="info-section">
            <div class="info-container">
                <h2>Breeding and Reproductive Strategies</h2>
                <p>Effective breeding management leads to successful reproduction and healthy calves:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Breeding Programs:</strong> Implement a breeding program that suits your herd's needs,
                        considering both natural and artificial insemination.</li>
                    <li><strong>Pregnancy Management:</strong> Monitor pregnant cows closely and prepare for calving by
                        ensuring a clean, stress-free environment.</li>
                    <li><strong>Calf Care:</strong> Ensure calves receive colostrum within the first few hours of life for
                        immunity and monitor their health closely.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Consult with breeding experts to optimize reproductive success in your herd.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Market Insights and Financial Management -->
